[
    {
        "content": "<p>Consider a goal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟹</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\implies Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7073em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟹</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I have not yet seen how to prove <strong>goals</strong> that have implications. I strongly suspect I will need to learn a new tactic to work with such goals.</p>\n<p>My question is - what's the general pattern for proving goals which are implications?</p>\n<p>I have tried searching the internet for guidance and can't find anything that helps (a beginner like me). </p>\n<p>I suspect the general pattern might be of the form:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>establish <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> as a hypothesis - but can't use <code>have</code> as that needs to be justified</li>\n<li>use <code>calc</code> or other means to arrive at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> - but how does lean know that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> was from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> - this looks like it needs a new instruction/tactic that I don't know.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 479942282,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730401153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Typically the first step is <code>intro hP</code>, which adds a hypothesis <code>hP : P</code> and changes the goal to <code>Q</code></p>",
        "id": 479942442,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1730401204
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks - I'll take a look.</p>\n<p>Can you say what the difference is between <code>intro h</code> and <code>intro x</code>? </p>\n<p>(<code>h</code> is a Proposition, <code>x</code> is a variable)</p>",
        "id": 479942897,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730401365
    },
    {
        "content": "<hr>\n<p>Actually I've tried this and run into a problem.</p>\n<p>If I want to prove <code>x^2 &gt; 1 → y = 0</code> (for example), then I need to <code>intro hP</code> where <code>hP : x^2 &gt; 1</code>.</p>\n<p>But I only know how to <code>have hP: x^2 &gt; 1</code> and this only works if I justify/prove <code>x^2 &gt; 1</code>.</p>\n<p>Here I need to add <code>hP</code> as an assumption, somehow.</p>",
        "id": 479944096,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730401863
    },
    {
        "content": "<hr>\n<p>experimenting I think I found this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">intro</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hP</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>is this correct?</p>",
        "id": 479944432,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730402013
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If lean says it's fine, it's fine, but note that you don't need the <code>x^2 &gt; 1</code>; just <code>intro hP</code> will work</p>",
        "id": 479946223,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1730402713
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Technically, there's no real difference between <code>intro x</code> where <code>x</code> is a variable and <code>intro h</code> where <code>h</code> is a proposition, but this is somehow a feature of lean's type theory that's not necessarily something to think a lot about - the upshot is that you can use <code>intro</code> in either case and it'll Just Work(TM)</p>",
        "id": 479946536,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1730402836
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am <strong>genuinely surprised</strong> <code>intro hP</code> just worked:</p>\n<p>for the goal state:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">⊢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≥</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"mi\">3</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>the code <code>intro hP</code>  results in </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℝ</span>\n<span class=\"n\">hP</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">4</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">⊢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≥</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"mi\">3</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is this because <code>intro hP</code> looks at the current goal and takes the LHS of an implication and turns that into a hypothesis?</p>",
        "id": 479947018,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730403022
    },
